World Series Potential Matchup: A Head-To-Head Comparison of Nathan Eovaldi and Zack Wheeler and An Analysis of the Matchup between Nathan Eovaldi and Bryce Harper

knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)

library(reshape) # Load tidyverse

For this analysis I will work with statcast data. There are a few pre-processing steps to go through, but I loaded in the modified data stored as statcast_2023.rda. This dataset contains all of the pitches from the 2023 MLB season.

load("statcast_2023.rda") # Load data
head(statcast)

Creating a simplified binary outcome to aid our analysis by assigning:

  • 0 - For strikes
  • -1 - For plays that result in an out
  • 1 - For a play that results in a positive outcome
# Create empty vector
outcome <- rep(NA, nrow(statcast))

#%in% = checking to see if something is in something else and returning T/F
# Set 0 for strikes
outcome[statcast$description %in% c("called_strike",
                                   "swinging_strike", 
                                   "swinging_strike_blocked")] <- 0
# Set -1 for plays that result in an out
outcome[statcast$events %in% c("field_out", 
                              "strikeout", 
                              "strikeout_double_play", 
                              "grounded_into_double_play", 
                              "fielders_choice_out",
                              "other_out")] <- -1

# Set 1 for positive plays
outcome[statcast$events %in% c("single",
                              "double",
                              "triple",
                              "walk",
                              "home_run")]  <- 1

Add the binary outcome to the statcast dataset and then drop rows where this or the pitch name are NA.

# Create copy of data frame
statcast_2 <- statcast
# Add outcome to copied data
statcast_2$outcome <- outcome
# Drop rows where outcome is NA
statcast_2 <- statcast_2[!is.na(statcast_2$outcome) &
                         !is.na(statcast_2$pitch_name),]

Choose at least one pitcher and batter from each of the teams in the upcoming world series games (NLDS between Diamondbacks and Phillies had not been completed at this time so this analysis compares the Rangers to the Phillies even though the Diamondbacks were the actual team in the World Series).

* Identify the fastest pitch of each pitcher

Nathan Eovaldi 

eovaldi <- statcast_2[statcast_2$pitcher_name == "Eovaldi, Nathan", ]
head(eovaldi)

The fastest individual pitch that Nathan Eovaldi threw was a Fastball that went 99.1 mph

which.max(eovaldi$release_speed)
## [1] 62

fastest_eovaldi$pitch_type
## [1] "FF"
fastest_eovaldi$release_speed
## [1] 99.1

Overall, Nathan Eovaldis fastest pitch was the fastball, which was 95.4 mph on average

aggregate(eovaldi$release_speed, list(eovaldi$pitch_type), FUN=mean)

The histograms of the pitch speeds for the fastballs thrown by Nathan Eovaldi and Zack Wheeler are shown above. One observation that I noticed is that Nathan Eovaldi has more outliers on his fastball pitch speed on both ends (fastballs thrown that were significantly faster or slower than the average speed) while Zach Weelers fastball speed was more consistent.

* Calculate the strengths and weaknesses of the players by the different pitch types.

Nathan Eovaldi 

# Set team to analyze
team <- "TEX"

# Extract unique pitch types
pitch_types <- unique(statcast_2$pitch_name)

# Create empty vectors to store results
hit <- strike <- out <- number <- average <- wp_change <- rep(NA, length(pitch_types))

# Loop through and calculate return for each pitch type
for(i in 1:length(pitch_types)){
  
  # Extract data for pitch type 
  temp <- statcast_2[statcast_2$pitch_name == pitch_types[i] &
                      statcast_2$pitcher_team == team,]
  
  # Calculate number of pitches thrown
  number[i] <- nrow(temp)
  # Calculate positive hits
  hit[i] <- sum(temp$outcome == 1, na.rm =TRUE)
  # Calculate strikes
  strike[i] <- sum(temp$outcome == 0, na.rm = TRUE)
  # Calculate outs 
  out[i] <- sum(temp$outcome == -1, na.rm = TRUE)
  # Calculate average
  average[i] <- mean(temp$outcome)
  # Calculate win probability change
  wp_change[i] <- mean(temp$win_prob_change, na.rm = TRUE)
  
}

# Join results together
res_table_1_pitch <- cbind.data.frame(pitch_types, number, hit, strike, out, average, wp_change)
# Extract unique pitch types
pitch_types <- unique(statcast_2$pitch_name)

# Set pitcher
pitcher <- "Eovaldi, Nathan"

# Create empty vectors to store results
hit <- strike <- out <- number <- average <- wp_change <- rep(NA, length(pitch_types))

# Loop through and calculate return for each pitch type
for(i in 1:length(pitch_types)){
  
  # Extract data for pitch type 
  temp <- statcast_2[statcast_2$pitch_name == pitch_types[i] &
                      statcast_2$pitcher_name == pitcher,]
  
  # Calculate number of pitches thrown
  number[i] <- nrow(temp)
  # Calculate positive hits
  hit[i] <- sum(temp$outcome == 1, na.rm =TRUE)
  # Calculate strikes
  strike[i] <- sum(temp$outcome == 0, na.rm = TRUE)
  # Calculate outs 
  out[i] <- sum(temp$outcome == -1, na.rm = TRUE)
  # Calculate average
  average[i] <- mean(temp$outcome)
  # Calculate win probability change
  wp_change[i] <- mean(temp$win_prob_change, na.rm = TRUE)
}

# Join results together
eovaldi_table <- cbind.data.frame(pitch_types, number, hit, strike, out, average, wp_change)
res_table_1_pitch[order(res_table_1_pitch$wp_change, decreasing = FALSE),]
# Create column with pitch type and number faced
eovaldi_table$pitch_num <- paste(eovaldi_table$pitch_types, ": ",
                                      eovaldi_table$number, sep = "")


# Create plot
g_8 <- ggplot(data = eovaldi_table, # Set dataset
              aes(x = pitch_num,  # Set x axis as pitch type
                  y= wp_change, # Set y as win probability change
                  fill = pitch_types)) + # Set fill as pitch type
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") + # Set geom bar for bar plot
  theme_bw() + # Set theme 
  coord_flip() + # Flip coordinates
  labs(x = "Pitch Types", # Set labels
       y = "Average Change in Batter Win Probability",
       title = "Change in Win probability by Pitch Type",
       subtitle = "") +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), # Remove grid
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), # Remove grid
        panel.border = element_blank(), # Remove grid
        panel.background = element_blank()) + # Remove grid
  guides(fill = NULL) # Turn off legend for fill

* Analyze the match up between at least one pitcher and batter. Describe what would be some good pitches to target in the match up for the pitcher and pitches to be cautious for the batter. 

name <- "Harper, Bryce"

# Create empty vectors to store results
hit <- strike <- out <- number <- average <- wp_change <- rep(NA, length(pitch_types))

# Loop through and calculate return for each pitch type
for(i in 1:length(pitch_types)){
  
  # Extract data for pitch type and team
  temp <- statcast_2[statcast_2$pitch_name == pitch_types[i] &
                      statcast_2$player_name == name,]
  
  # Calculate number of pitches thrown
  number[i] <- nrow(temp)
  # Calculate positive hits
  hit[i] <- sum(temp$outcome == 1, na.rm =TRUE)
  # Calculate strikes
  strike[i] <- sum(temp$outcome == 0, na.rm = TRUE)
  # Calculate outs 
  out[i] <- sum(temp$outcome == -1, na.rm = TRUE)
  # Calculate average
  average[i] <- mean(temp$outcome)
  # Calculate win probability change
  wp_change[i] <- mean(temp$win_prob_change, na.rm = TRUE)
  
}

This matchup will likely favor Nathan Eovaldi if he leans on his split-finger, but Bryce Harper will have an advantage if Eovaldi relies on his curveball too heavily. Eovaldis strongest pitch is the split-finger because it has a combination of a positive impact on his win probability and a negative impact on opponents batting averages against the pitch. On the contrary, the split-finger is one of Bryce Harpers weakest pitches because it has the strongest negative impact on his change in win probability. While Harpers overall offensive statistics were very strong in the 2023 season, he has only faced 18 split-fingers this season so that would be a good pitch to target for him. This is advantageous for Eovaldi because the split-finger is the pitch he throws the second most frequently behind his curveball. However, Eovaldis fallback pitch, the curveball, is one of Bryce Harpers strongest pitches to hit. Especially if Eovaldi falls behind in the count and must fall back on his curveball, the matchup would favor Harper. Sliders seem to favor Eovaldi, cutters favor Harper, and the 4-Seam fastball is closer to neutral although it slightly favors Eovaldi.
